Where “muscle memory” actually lives

When you repeat an action (throw, type, clear a room), a few things happen:

1) Brain circuits get refined

* motor cortex (planning/command)
* basal ganglia (habit formation)
* cerebellum (timing + precision)

2) Spinal cord patterns get encoded

* fast, semi-automatic loops
* less need to route everything through conscious control

3) The body adapts

* muscles get stronger and more efficient
* tendons stiffen or relax appropriately
* sensors in the body improve feedback

So when people say “it’s in the muscle,” what they’re feeling is:

the action no longer needs conscious thought

